article.description:
Mwadi Mabika had 27 points and 10 rebounds
and Lisa Leslie, playing through foul trouble, added 14 points and 14 rebounds to lead the Los Angeles Sparks to a 73-58 victory over the Indiana Fever on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Mabika collects 27 points, 10 rebounds
article.linkText: Mabika scores 27 as Sparks shut down Fever
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Los Angeles Sparks trailed by six points, Lisa Leslie had five fouls and the Indiana Fever seemed poised to make a run at a surprise victory. Then Los Angeles showed why it is the defending WNBA champion, using a 20-4 run run midway through the second half to put the game away. Mwadi Mabika had 27 points and 10 rebounds, and Leslie, playing through foul trouble, added 14 points and 14 rebounds to lead the Los Angeles Sparks to a 73-58 victory Wednesday night over the Indiana Fever. Leslie, coming off her All-Star game MVP performance, was called for three fouls in the first two minutes of the second half, giving her five and sending her to the bench. "It's kind of weird because I actually got three offensive fouls,'' Leslie said. "I just had to make the adjustment to not play defense. That's not something I'm used to doing.'' She left with the game tied at 36, but consecutive 3-pointers by Rita Williams and Tamika Catchings gave the Fever a 46-40 lead. Catchings, who led the East in scoring in the All-Star game, led the Fever with 15 points but was only 5-for-16 from the field. Olympia Scott-Richardson had 12 points and 10 rebounds for Indiana. The Sparks (16-3) scored six straight points and eventually took the lead for good at 50-48 on a basket by DeLisha Milton. They would push the lead to 60-50, capping the run. Nikki McCray, who added 11 points, hit a 3 with 4:30 remaining as the Fever (8-12) pulled to 60-53. It was as close as they would get. Los Angeles coach Michael Cooper said switching at halftime from a man-to-man defense to a 2-3 zone was the difference. "That kind of held them down a little bit as far as taking shots over the top,'' he said. "I believe man-to-man is the way to go, but it is a good part of our defense we can use.'' Indiana Fever coach Nell Fortner said her team couldn't make the necessary adjustments. "We lost our legs against the zone,'' Fortner said. "We've got the shooters to break the zone and we will do it.'' Milton had 11 points and Tamecka Dixon 10 for the Sparks. Leslie and Mabika combined for 14 rebounds in the first half, helping the Sparks to a 11-0 advantage in second-chance points. Catchings picked up two fouls before Los Angeles scored but played all but one minute in the first half. The Fever led by as many as six but went into halftime tied at 32. Scott-Richardson said the Fever couldn't afford to waste any more opportunities if they hoped to reach the postseason for the first time. "We found out we have the ability to play with a league-leading team that knows how to win,'' she said. "We are still learning how to win. Our goal is to be in the playoffs.'' Game notes
Some fans held signs that said Catchings was the true All-Star MVP. ... Vernon Forrest, the WBC welterweight champion, and "Sugar'' Shane Mosley were at the game. Forrest will defend his title Saturday against Mosley at Conseco Fieldhouse. ... Tennessee coach Pat Summitt and Connecticut coach Geno Auriemma also were at the game. ... Al Harrington, wearing a Yankees jersey and cap, and Ron Artest of the Pacers were in attendance as was three-time WNBA MVP Cynthia Cooper.
